article.headline: Tennessee makes title game after blitzing Army 96-44
article.linkText: Another blowout keeps bench busy for No. 5 Tennessee
article.story:
CAROLINA, Puerto Rico -- Tennessee's bench got a lot of
playing time for the second consecutive night, so the starters should
be well rested when they play for the championship of the
San Juan Shootout.

	   Tennessee beat Army 96-44 Saturday and meet Saint Louis on Sunday for
the title. A night earlier, the Lady Vols beat Puerto Rico-Mayaguez
136-26.

	   On Saturday, Kara Lawson led a barrage of 3-point baskets,
scoring 20 points for Tennessee (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today; No. 4 Associated Press) in the second round
of the tournament.

	   Freshman reserve Shanna Zolman added 15 points from off the
bench on 4-for-7 shooting.

	   ''These kind of games favor the bench,'' coach Pat Summitt said.
''They're getting a lot of minutes and a lot of confidence.''

	   Lawson made four of six 3-point attempts, and Tennessee (4-1)
wound up 12-for-23 from beyond the arc.

	   ''It's been one of my goals,'' Jackson said. ''Now it's on to
other goals.''

	   Gwen Jackson made three of four from long range and scored 13
points to surpass the 1,000 for her career.

	   ''We had very good ball movement and when that happens we get
real good looks for 3-pointers,'' Summitt said.

	   Army (1-3) started well, taking a 6-4 lead. But Tennessee
quickly found the range and a 16-point run included two 3-pointers
by Brittany Jackson. Tennessee had a 25-8 lead with 12:03
remaining in the first half.

	   Army faces the Puerto Rico-Mayaguez in the consolation
game. Saint Louis beat the Puerto Rico-Mayaguez 90-32 earlier
Saturday.

	   Katie Macfarlane paced Army with 12 points.
